com.riskybusiness.neural

Class NeuralNet

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.riskybusiness.neural.NeuralNet
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable

    public class NeuralNet
extends Object
implements Serializable

         A NeuralNet is a set of Neurons interconnected by Synapses to compute a set of outputs. This is done by feeding the NeuralNet a set of inputs into a set of Neurons, and calling the interconnected Synapses Synapse.feedForward() methods. Once all of the Synapses have fed the outputs forward, the output layer can be caluculated. Unlike many other implementations of a neural network, NeuralNet has no way of knowing which Neuron is part of the input, hidden or output layer. The only way a NeuralNet has to determine this when firing is to determine if a Neuron can fire or not as well as how many Synapses have already fired. More can be seen in fire(float[][]). Also note that this network allows the input layer to have mutliple inputs to them.

         As of version 1.0, there is no way of training the network. RiskyBusiness hopes to do this via backpropagation, but this may prove difficult given our current implementation of the layers. Also, the network as a whole has no way of making a reccurent Neuron; that is to say, there is no way of having a Neuron who is connected to itself. Future implementations may send in a parameter to the Neuron class that will tell its Neurons fire method to not return false if it is not full but has one space left that happens to be itself. The fire method will have to be dealt with as well, as well as the Synapse feedForward method.

    Since:
    1.6

    • Constructor Detail

      • NeuralNet

        public NeuralNet(Neuron[] neurons,
         Synapse[] synapses)

        Makes a NeuralNet whose Neurons and Synapses have already been previously made. Make sure that the neuron list is sorted by layer prevolence. This is described as the input layer first (in the order of relevant inputs), then the first hidden layer, then the third...nth layer, and finally the output layer. It is imperative that this order be met in order for the methods of this class to work properly.

        Parameters:
        neurons - The Neurons that make up this network.
        synapses - The Synapses that make up this network.

      • NeuralNet

        public NeuralNet(int inputLayerRows,
         int outputLayerRows,
         int... hiddenLayerRows)

        Constructs a NeuralNet with the given amount of Neurons for the input layer, output layer, and consequent hiddenLayers. All of these layers are perfectly interconnected. This means that each input Neuron sends its output to exactly every hidden Neuron in the next layer, and so on for every layer. The default Neuron that is used is the SigmoidNeuron. The exception to this rule is the output layer, which is made up of Stepneurons.

        Parameters:
        inputLayerRows - The amount of Neurons in the input layer.
        outputLayerRows - The amount of Neurons in the output layer.
        hiddenLayerRows - Each index corresponds to another hidden layer, with the amount of Neurons in the hidden layer corresponding to the value at that index.

      • fire

        public float[] fire(float[][] inputs)
             throws InvalidNeuronInputException

        Populates the NeuralNet with the inputs and calculates their corresponding output. This will leave the NeuralNet with the Neurons filled with the input values that they would received while firing.

        Parameters:
        inputs - The inputs to the NeuralNet. These values are determined in that each list accessed in from the inputs list corresponds to an input Neuron in the NeuralNet.
        Returns:
        The results from the output layer, in order.
        Throws:
        InvalidNeuronInputException - When the amount of inputs given is greater than that of the amount of Neurons in the NeuralNet, or when the amount of inputs given is greater than that of the input layer.
        See Also:
        Neuron.fire(), Synapse.feedForward()

      • train

        public void train(float[] desired,
         float[][] inputs)
           throws InvalidNeuronOutputException

        Trains the NeuralNet in the traditional sense, using backpropagation. This method requires that the type of activation function used by each Neuron is continuous and differentiable. This means that a StepNeuron can only be used for the output layer if you are using this method.

        Parameters:
        desired - The desired outputs from the NeuralNet.
        inputs - The inputs to send to the NeuralNet.
        Throws:
        InvalidNeuronOutputException - If the given size of outputs is not equal to that of the neural network's output layer.
        See Also:
        fire(float[][])
